Problem #1

Run a simulation to build evidence for or against the following claim: The simple linear regression line fitted to the points in the scatter plot of \(Y\) versus \(\widehat{Y}\) has zero intercept and a unit slope.

To do this, simulate some data with a known slope and intercept parameters, then fit an SLR model to the data, and plot the response vs the fitted values.

set.seed(1111)

x = rnorm(275, 1, 3)
z = rnorm(275, -1, 2)
c = rnorm(275, 0, 1)

y = (x + z - c)

mod = lm(y ~ c)
summary(mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ c)
##

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

yHat = fitted.values(mod)

(d) Plot the residuals (y) against the fitted values (x). Does the variability in the residuals look constant as the fitted values increase? Interpret why that might be important. Also, produce a normal QQ-plot of the residuals. If the points of the QQ-plot roughly follow the line \(y = x\), then we dont have evidence against normality of the residuals. How does the QQ-plot look for these residuals?

radioSales.resid = resid(radioSales)
plot(radioSales.resid)

print("Yes, with the exception of 2 samples, this a good indication that the difference between the observed and fitted data across the samples is very similar or constant.")
## [1] "Yes, with the exception of 2 samples, this a good indication that the difference between the observed and fitted data across the samples is very similar or constant."
radioSales.stdres = rstandard(radioSales)
qqnorm(radioSales.stdres)
qqline(radioSales.stdres, col = "red")

print("The points of the QQ-plot roughly follow the line (y = x), thus we don't have evidence against normality of the residuals.")
## [1] "The points of the QQ-plot roughly follow the line (y = x), thus we don't have evidence against normality of the residuals."

(e) We learned that, often, the goal of regression is to make predictions on new data. Lets see how well the model does at predicting values that we left out of the training set.

\[ MSE = \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}\bigg(y_i - \widehat{y}_i \bigg)^2.\]

Compute the MSE for the data in the training set, and for data in the testing set. Which one is lower? Explain why you think its lower.
